    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1951-01-05T05:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1951-01-05T05:00:00-05:00" n="19"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d19">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">693.95/1–551: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in the Republic of China</hi> (<persName
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Rankin</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">top secret</hi>
                        <lb/>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">priority</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Taipei</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1951-01-05T18:00:00+08:00"
                            >January 5, 1951—6 p. m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>887. Contents <gloss target="#t_Depcirtel1">Depcirtel</gloss> 334, January 3,
                    discussed Foreign Minister<note n="1" xml:id="d19fn1">George Yen.</note> whose
                    initial reactions as follows: <list>
                        <label>1.</label>
                        <item>Chinese Government naturally favors strongest practicable stand
                            against Chinese Communists and will go along with US in this
                            sense.</item>
                        <label>2.</label>
                        <item>Foreign Minister agrees events have overtaken Six Power Resolution and
                            considers highly important to <gloss target="#t_UNO1">UNO</gloss>
                            prestige and US leadership that events not be allowed overtake next move
                            decided on.</item>
                        <label>3.</label>
                        <item>Chinese Government would support either adoption Six Power Resolution
                            suitably amended, or new <gloss target="#t_GA1">GA</gloss> resolution
                            branding Chinese Communists as aggressors and calling for collective
                            action, whichever seems likely prove more appropriate.</item>
                        <pb facs="0043" n="27" xml:id="pg_27"/>
                        <label>4.</label>
                        <item>Foreign Minister feels questions of breaking diplomatic relations with
                            Peking and imposing embargoes, et cetera, depend almost entirely on
                            position taken by UK, although effective control of exports and
                            reexports from all North and South American sources would also be
                            important factor.</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <p>Foreign Minister will discuss these matters with his colleagues in government and
                    let me have any further significant ideas that may develop.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Rankin</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
